  "prompt": "Are there international laws against money laundering?",
  "response": "Yes, there are several international laws and initiatives aimed at combating money laundering:\n\n1. Financial Action Task Force (FATF)\n- An intergovernmental organization that sets standards for anti-money laundering policies\n- Develops recommendations that countries should implement\n\n2. United Nations Conventions\n- UN Convention against Transnational Organized Crime\n- UN Convention against Corruption\n- Provide frameworks for international cooperation against money laundering\n\n3. Basel Committee on Banking Supervision\n- Provides guidelines for banks to prevent money laundering\n\n4. International Monetary Fund (IMF) guidelines\n- Supports countries in developing anti-money laundering regulations\n\n5. Individual Country Laws\n- Most countries have their own domestic anti-money laundering laws\n- Often require financial institutions to report suspicious transactions\n- Mandate customer identification and record-keeping\n\n6. Bank Secrecy Act (US)\n- Requires financial institutions to assist government agencies in detecting and preventing money laundering\n\nThese laws and initiatives typically focus on:\n- Requiring financial transparency\n- Establishing reporting mechanisms\n- Creating mechanisms for international cooperation\n- Implementing penalties for non-compliance\n\nWhile no single global law exists, these frameworks work together to combat money laundering internationally.",
